# Code Review & Refactor Best Practices (MeApp Android)

## 1. Analyze the Existing Code
- Carefully review the current implementation for architecture, logic, and design patterns.
- Identify code smells, anti-patterns, or deviations from Android best practices.
- Check for maintainability, readability, and separation of concerns.

## 2. Simplify and Optimize
- Refactor code to improve clarity, reduce complexity, and eliminate redundancy.
- Extract logic into helper functions or classes where appropriate.
- Prefer composition over inheritance.
- Remove unnecessary nesting and inline complex initializations into private helpers.
- Ensure code is DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) and SOLID.

## 3. Scalability & Performance
- Ensure the codebase is modular and easy to extend.
- Use efficient data structures and algorithms.
- Avoid unnecessary recompositions or allocations in Compose.
- Minimize memory and CPU usage, especially in UI and background operations.

## 4. Strict Android & Jetpack Compose Standards
- Follow the latest Android and Jetpack Compose best practices.
- Use dependency injection (Hilt/Dagger) for all dependencies.
- No business logic in UI composables.
- All strings, dimensions, and colors must be externalized (no hardcoding).
- Use the app's design system for all UI elements.
- Add KDoc for all public classes, functions, and properties.
- Ensure accessibility (content descriptions, etc.).
- Use previews for all composables.
- Use proper state management (ViewModel, StateFlow, etc.).
- Use only one main composable per file (with previews).

## 5. Testing and Validation
- Add or update unit tests and UI tests as needed.
- Ensure all code paths are covered and edge cases are handled.

## 6. Build and Fix Until Clean
- After all changes, **run a full build of the Android application**.
- If any errors or warnings are present, fix them immediately.
- Repeat the build and fix process until the codebase is clean and the app runs without issues.

---

**Summary:**
> For every feature or refactor: 1. Analyze → 2. Simplify/Optimize → 3. Ensure Scalability/Performance → 4. Enforce Android/Compose Standards → 5. Test → 6. Build and Fix Until Clean.

---

This rule must be followed for all future code changes and reviews.
